<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>DrGos</title><link>https://drgos.com/</link><description>Recent content on DrGos</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Thu, 01 Oct 2020 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://drgos.com/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>How to host you site on Github for free!</title><link>https://drgos.com/p/how-to-host-you-site-on-github-for-free/</link><pubDate>Thu, 01 Oct 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://drgos.com/p/how-to-host-you-site-on-github-for-free/</guid><description>&lt;img src="https://drgos.com/p/how-to-host-you-site-on-github-for-free/the-creative-exchange-d2zvqp3fpro-unsplash.jpg" alt="Featured image of post How to host you site on Github for free!" />&lt;p>I&amp;rsquo;ve decided to start a blog and what better hello world post than how I&amp;rsquo;ve set it up. But first lets talk about what is Hugo.&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="what-is-hugo">What is Hugo?&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>&lt;figure
>
&lt;a href="https://drgos.com/images/2560px-Logo_of_Hugo_the_static_website_generator.png" >
&lt;img src="https://drgos.com/images/2560px-Logo_of_Hugo_the_static_website_generator.png"
loading="lazy"
alt="2560px-Logo_of_Hugo_the_static_website_generator.svg.png">
&lt;/a>
&lt;figcaption>2560px-Logo_of_Hugo_the_static_website_generator.svg.png&lt;/figcaption>
&lt;/figure>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>According to their &lt;a class="link" href="https://gohugo.io/about/what-is-hugo/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>site&lt;/a> Hugo is a fast and modern static site generator written in Go, and designed to make website creation fun again.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Put it in layman terms &lt;a class="link" href="https://gohugo.io/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Hugo&lt;/a> is a tool that generates a full static HTML website based on raw data and a set of templates. Essentially, Hugo automates the task of coding individual HTML pages and gets those pages ready to serve to users ahead of time. The nice thing about Hugo is that even though is written in go, you don&amp;rsquo;t need to have go installed on your machine.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The raw data is the content you write in &lt;a class="link" href="https://www.markdownguide.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Markdown&lt;/a>, a format that widely used in lots of editors.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The template is the theme that you chose for your site.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>My process for writing a blog post is:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>write a post using &lt;a class="link" href="https://code.visualstudio.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>VSCode&lt;/a>. I have install the &lt;a class="link" href="https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=zaaack.markdown-editor" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Markdown Editor&lt;/a> to make it easier to arrange the post and preview it, but lately I started using it less and less.
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>When I&amp;rsquo;m on the move and don&amp;rsquo;t have access to my PC, I use VSCode from &lt;a class="link" href="https://www.gitpod.io/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>GitPod&lt;/a>.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;/li>
&lt;li>then commit the post to the GitHub repository&lt;/li>
&lt;li>using GitHub Actions, deploy the post to a separate repository created for GitHub Pages.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;h2 id="install-hugo">Install Hugo&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>The first think we need to do is to install the Hugo CLI, to be able to test locally our changes before pushing them to &lt;a class="link" href="https://github.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Github&lt;/a>. Depending on your operating system you need to do the following:&lt;/p>
&lt;h3 id="mac-os">Mac OS:&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>If you use &lt;a class="link" href="https://brew.sh/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Homebrew&lt;/a>, run the brew install command in your terminal to install Hugo:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">brew install hugo
&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;p>or if you use &lt;a class="link" href="https://www.macports.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>MacPorts&lt;/a> run the following command:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">port install hugo
&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;p>To validate the installation run:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">hugo version
&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;h3 id="windows">Windows:&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>There are 2 methods of installing Hugo on windows:&lt;/p>
&lt;h3 id="method-1---using-chocolateyhttpschocolateyorg">Method 1 - Using &lt;a class="link" href="https://chocolatey.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Chocolatey&lt;/a>:&lt;/h3>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">choco install hugo --confirm
&lt;span class="c1"># Or if you need the “extended” Sass/SCSS version:&lt;/span>
choco install hugo-extended -confirm
&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;h3 id="method-2---manual-installation">Method 2 - Manual Installation&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>The Hugo GitHub repository contains pre-built versions of the Hugo command-line tool for various operating systems, which can be found on &lt;a class="link" href="https://github.com/gohugoio/hugo/releases" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>the Releases page&lt;/a>.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>For more instruction on installing these releases, refer to &lt;a class="link" href="https://gohugo.io/getting-started/installing/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Hugo&amp;rsquo;s install guide.&lt;/a>&lt;/p>
&lt;h3 id="linux">Linux&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>Based on your operating system you can use one of the following commands:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">&lt;span class="c1"># Debian / Ubuntu&lt;/span>
sudo apt-get install hugo
&lt;span class="c1"># Arch / Manjaro&lt;/span>
sudo pacman -Syu hugo
&lt;span class="c1"># Fedora, Red Hat and CentOS&lt;/span>
sudo dnf install hugo
&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;p>For other distributions or operating systems visit the &lt;a class="link" href="https://gohugo.io/getting-started/installing/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Hugo&amp;rsquo;s install guide.&lt;/a>&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="create-a-hugo-site">Create a Hugo site&lt;/h2>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>If you don&amp;rsquo;t have any knowledge of git, before you continue take a look at the &lt;a class="link" href="https://guides.github.com/introduction/git-handbook/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Git Handbook&lt;/a> and the &lt;a class="link" href="https://guides.github.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>GitHub Guides Page&lt;/a>
If you want to have an in depth knowledge of Git read the &lt;a class="link" href="https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Git Book&lt;/a>&lt;/p>
&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;p>Now that you have Hugo install is time to create your own site and run it locally:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">&lt;span class="c1"># create site&lt;/span>
hugo new site myblog-name
&lt;span class="c1"># move into newly created site&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="nb">cd&lt;/span> myblog-name
&lt;span class="c1"># start the hugo server. The server will point to http://localhost:1313/&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="c1"># the -D option will include content marked as draft. More info at https://gohugo.io/commands/hugo_server/&lt;/span>
hugo server -D
&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;p>Now that the site is created, comes the hardest part. Picking up a &lt;a class="link" href="https://themes.gohugo.io/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>theme&lt;/a>. This is the steps were I&amp;rsquo;ve spend the most time on and probably the part of my blog where I tinker the most until now. At the time of the writting I&amp;rsquo;m using &lt;a class="link" href="https://github.com/CaiJimmy/hugo-theme-stack" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Hugo Theme Stack.&lt;/a> My recommendation is that if you are using Git to manage your Hugo site, add the themes as a submodule.&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">&lt;span class="c1"># git submodule add repo-url&lt;/span>
git submodule add https://github.com/CaiJimmy/hugo-theme-stack/ themes/hugo-theme-stack
&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;p>If it&amp;rsquo;s your first time using this theme, take a look at exampleSite folder, which includes an example config.yaml with all available parameters.&lt;/p>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>If you plan to test out multiple themes, remember to backup your config file so you can easily come back to a previous version, or create a branch for each theme that you test out. This way when you find the one it&amp;rsquo;s easy to switch to it and start working.&lt;/p>
